%%TITLE
Frequency and genotype distribution of multiple human papillomavirus infections in cancer of the head and neck in a Mexican population.
%%ABSTRACT
The aim of this study was to determine the frequency and genotype distribution of single and multiple human papillomavirus (HPV) infections in head and neck squamous cell carcinomas (HNSCCs) in a Mexican population and to assess their associations with smoking and drinking habits and clinicopathologic characteristics.A cross-sectional study was performed on a sample of patients diagnosed with HNSCCs. Tumor DNA was amplified using polymerase chain reaction with HPV consensus and multiplex primers. The associations among HPV status, survival, and clinical characteristics were analyzed.Sixteen of the 43 HNSCCs were HPV positive. HPV16 was the most prevalent type, with single infections present in 5 cases, whereas another 5 cases were combined with HPV56 infection. There was a significant association between HPV infection and oropharyngeal cancers. HPV positivity was associated with overall survival at a nearly significant P level of 0.06.Our data support the importance of HPV infection in oropharyngeal cancer, with a trend toward higher survival in HPV-positive cases.
%%MATERIAL AND METHODS
A cross-sectional study was performed. Samples were collected from consecutive patients with HNSCC who had a diagnosis of squamous cell carcinoma of the oral cavity, oropharynx, larynx, parotid, maxillary antrum, or pharynx and who attended the Head and Neck Ser- vice at the Instituto Nacional de Cancerología of Mex- ico City (INCan) between January 2007 and August 2008. Forty-three patients, including 16 women and 27 men who had not received previous treatment, were included in the study. All patients signed written in- formed consent according to the recommendations of the Institutional Review Board of the INCan. Clinical and demographic data were collected from each patient file. A demographic questionnaire including history of tobacco and alcohol consumption was administered to each patient. Correlations with HPV status were ana- lyzed with respect to treatment (surgery, radiation, and chemotherapy) and survival. A biopsy was taken from the lesion and separated into 2 fragments: 1 section was used for histopathological examination that was con- firmed by a single pathologist, and the other section
was frozen at -70°C for DNA extraction using the phenol-chloroform method and subsequent HPV identification through polymerase chain reaction (PCR) amplification. The 1-globin gene was PCR amplified
for a quality assessment.HPV was detected by PCR
amplification using 3 sets of consensus primers for the
L1 gene: MY09/MY11, L1C1/L1C2, and GP5+/ GP6.
For HPV genotyping, direct sequencing of the PCR products and sequence analysis of the positive samples was performed using the BLAST program ( ). Multiple HPV infec- tions were detected using the nested multiplex PCR method based on consensus and type-specific primers amplifying the E6/E7 region, as previously described. Briefly, DNA samples were subjected to a first-round amplification using the following consensus primers: forward, GP-E6-3F (5-GGG WGK KAC TGA AAT CGGT-3); and reverse, GP-E7-5B (5-CTG AGC TGT CAR NTA ATT GCT CA-3) and GP-E7-6B (5-TCC
TCT GAG TYG YCT AAT TGC TC-3), to generate an amplicon ranging from 602 to 666 bp in size. The GP-E6/E7 PCR products were subsequently amplified with type-specific nested primers and arranged in 4
cocktails for the following HPV genotypes: cocktail I (HPV16, -18, -31, -59, and -45), cocktail II
(HPV33, -6/11, -58, -52, and -56), cocktail III
(HPV35, -42, -43, and -44), and cocktail IV
(HPV68, -39, -51, and -66). The identification of each HPV genotype was achieved by evaluating the
size of the specific PCR product by electrophoresis on a 2% agarose gel. Validation of a representative set of cases was performed through direct sequencing of the product bands isolated from the agarose gels.
Statistical analysis
For descriptive purposes, the variables were summa- rized as proportions expressed as percentages, arith- metic means and standard deviations (SD), and me- dian (Md) values and ranges, as deemed appropriate. For some analyses, the tumor stages were recatego- rized from the original 4 levels into dichotomic 2-level variables, collapsing the TNM I-II levels into 1 category and the TNM III-IV levels into another. Cumulative smoking or drinking exposure was cal- culated as the product of the daily number of ciga- rettes (or alcoholic drinks) multiplied by years of exposure. Survival analysis was performed for over- all survival (OS) and disease-free survival (DFS) following the Kaplan-Meier procedure. Statistical significance was estimated by the Wilcoxon Mann- Whitney rank-sum test for dimensional variables or Fisher’s exact test for contingency tables and with the log-rank test for the comparison of survival
curves. The two-tailed a level was set at 0.05. Calculations were performed using Stata software (StataCorp, College Station, TX).
